{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b5b14a9-77df-4064-a071-c908522be5b7","content":"Neither — use **`dotnet watch`** to benefit from hot reload.\n\n- **`dotnet watch run`** — re-runs your app when files change.\n- **`dotnet watch test`** — re-runs tests when files change.\n\nBoth `dotnet test` and `dotnet run` are single-shot commands; they don't monitor for file changes. `dotnet watch` is the wrapper that provides the hot reload / live-reload experience.\n\nFor your test project, you'd use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test\n```\n\nThis will automatically re-run your tests whenever you save a change to your source files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"591ec780-ec18-4744-8677-c766172a1520","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET hot reload functionality - specifically whether `dotnet test` or `dotnet run` benefits from hot reload. Let me look at the files in the working directory to understand the context better.","outputTokens":204,"requestId":"4C30:2BC959:C1356C:F086F5:6A0133D4"},"id":"ea47b808-0218-4992-841f-a7c855ff8718","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:41:46.193Z","parentId":"3375f33b-cc56-4e51-b93f-29ab08f373fe"}
